		h1.pb-3 Sexual assault
		p Source:
			a(href="https://www.womenshealth.gov/a-z-topics/sexual-assault")  Women's Health Gov

		h3 What is sexual assault
		p Sexual assault is any type of sexual activity, including rape, that you do not agree to. Also called sexual violence or abuse, sexual assault is never your fault.

		p Sexual assault can include:
		ul
			li Any type of sexual contact with someone who cannot consent, such as someone who is underage, has an intellectual disability, or is passed out
			li Rape
			li Attempted rape
			li Sexual coercion
			li Sexual contact with a child
			li Fondling or unwanted touching above or under clothes
		
		p Sexual assault can also be verbal or visual. It is anything that forces a person to join in unwanted sexual contact or attention. Examples can include:

			li Voyeurism, or peeping (when someone watches private sexual acts without consent)
			li Exhibitionism (when someone exposes himself or herself in public)
			li Sexual harassment or threats
			li Forcing someone to pose for sexual pictures

		h3 How to respond in the moment
		p Sexual coercion is not your fault. If you are feeling pressured to do something you don't want to do, speak up or leave the situation. It is better to risk a relationship ending or hurting someone's feelings than to do something you aren't ready or willing to do.
		p Some possible responses include:
		ul
			li "I do like you, but I'm not ready for sex."
			li "If you really care for me, you'll respect that I don't want to have sex."
			li "I don't owe you an explanation or anything at all."
		p Be clear and direct with the person coercing you. Tell him or her how you feel and what you do not want to do. If the other person is not listening to you, leave the situation. If you or your family is in physical danger, try to get away from the person as quickly as possible. Call 998 if you are in immediate danger.

		h3 How to get help after sexual assault
		p After a sexual assault, you may feel fear, shame, guilt, or shock. These feelings are normal. But sexual assault is never your fault. It may be frightening to think about talking about the assault, but it is important to get help.
		p
			strong Call public safety and residential education. There is help available.

		h3 How can I help someone who has been assaulted?
		p You can help a friend or family member who has been sexually assaulted by listening, offering comfort, and not judging. Reinforce the message that she or he is not at fault and that it is natural to feel angry, confused, or ashamed — or any combination of feelings.

		p Ask your loved one if they would like you to go with them to the hospital or to counseling. If they decide to report the crime to the police, ask if they would like you to go with them. Let them know that professional help is available. Let them know about the hotlines to call and talk to someone.
